Classification and regression trees for linguistic analysis

Jason Grafmiller

June 6, 2018

In this tutorial, well go over the basics of how to use classification, regression, and conditional inference trees, more generally referred to as decision tree models. The basic methods have been around for a while (see Breiman 1998[1984]), but they are relatively new to linguistics. One of the first papers to utilize this technique, and the related technique of random forests, in linguistics was Tagliamonte & Baayen (2012), but the tree & forest method has been gaining ground as a useful alternative to other methods such as regression in recent years (Bernaisch et al. 2014; Szmrecsanyi et al. 2016a; Tagliamonte et al. 2016).

Lets get started!

Setup

Before we get started, lets load our basic libraries.

# basic data wrangling & plotting
library(tidyverse)
library(reshape2)
library(gridExtra)

# for the trees
library(rpart)
library(partykit)

What are classification and regression trees?

Decision tree models like classification and regression trees (CARTs) are similar in spirit to regression in that they are used to predict a response \(Y\) from a set of predictors \(X_1, X_2,...,X_n\). There are several packages in R for computing CARTs and we will briefly look at a couple of them here, namely the rpart and partykit packages.

There are generally two types of decision trees:

  • Classification trees are used when you want to predict a categorical response. That is, the dependent variable can be assigned to 2 or more discrete classes, values, or labels.
  • Regression trees are used when you want to predict a continuous response. That is, the dependent variable can take any of an infinite range of numerical values.

One of the major differences between tree models and standard regression models is that the latter are global models, in the sense that the prediction formula is assumed to hold over the entire data space. This means that in the simple case of a regression formula without any interactions,

\[y = \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \beta_3x_3\]

the effect of predictor \(x_1\) on the response \(y\) is assumed to be the same no matter what the values of predictors \(x_2\) and \(x_3\) may be. This is not so with tree models.

The idea behind tree models is to divide the data space into smaller and smaller non-overlapping partitions, to which simpler models can be applied. Tree models use a top-down approach, in which we begin at the top of the tree where all observations are included in a single region and successively split the data space into new branches (subregions) down the tree. Most tree algorithms are greedy in that they consider only the best split for the current region of the data. That is, they dont care about what splits have come before, or what splits may come after the current node. Splitting continues until some threshold is reached, and how that threshold is defined can have a major impact on the results.

Terminology

A bit of terminology:

  • Nodes: Points at which a splitting decision is made. Each node represents a (sub)section of the dataset. The Root node is the node at the top of the tree which represents the entire sample prior to any splitting.
  • Branches: Subsections of the entire tree (a,so called sub-trees)
  • Leaves / Terminal nodes: Nodes at the bottom of the tree where no further split is made.
  • Parent / Child nodes: Super- and subordinate nodes are referred to as parent and child nodes respectively.

In all decision trees, the leaves of the tree (terminal nodes) give us predictions about our response for the subregion of the dataset that the leaves represent.

  • For classification trees, the leaves of the tree (terminal nodes) give us predictions about which class is mostly likely for that subregion of the data. This is measured simply as the class with the most observations, i.e.the class that makes up the largest proportion of the data.
  • For regression trees, the prediction is just the mean value of the response for the observations in a given subregion. So if a data point falls into that region, our prediction for its response will be the average response in that region.

For this tutorial, we will focus on methods that use binary splits, though thereare methods for producing trees with more than two branches, e.g.with J48() in the RWeka package.

Splitting criteria

One of the most important factors affecting the accuracy of tree models is the method that the tree-growing algorithm uses to determine where and when to make a split. Remember, the idea is to find the best split at any given point, so the question becomes, how to determine the best split.

Decision trees use different algorithms to find the best split, and Ill briefly mention the most common here. But first, some more terminology

When talking about trees, we often talk about the homogeneity or purity of a given region of the data with respect to the distribution of the response variable. If you consider the plots below, its fairly easy to see which plot is the most homogeneous or pure.

Conversely, we can describe a region in terms of its impurity, in which case we can think of splitting a node as an attempt to partition the data in a manner that minimizes the impurity in the resulting subsets. Splitting is thus driven by the goal of impurity reduction. The goal is to divide the data up into subsets that are as homogenous or pure as we can possibly get based on the values of our predictors.

Datasets

For for classification trees well use two datasets from studies of syntactic alternations in English.

# These two are big files so I have saved them as more efficient .rds files.
# These are not readable with other programs, e.g. Excel, but they take up
# less space and are quicker to load.
gens <- readRDS("data/written_genitives.rds") %>% as.tibble
rels <- readRDS("data/object_relatives.rds") %>% as.tibble
# read from usual .csv file
english <- read.csv("data/english_word_decisions.csv") %>% as.tibble

Dataset written_genitives.rds

This is a dataset of English genitive constructions taken from the Brown and Frown corpora of written US English in the 1960s and 1990s, respectively. It contains all genitive tokens (of-gentives, as in the best interest of both governments; and the s-genitive, as in both governments best interest) found in five different fiction and nonfiction genres. This data was collected and annotated to investigate the infuence of a number of factor on writers choice of genitive construction (see Grafmiller 2014).

  1. the presidents assertion [s-genitive]
  2. the contour of her face [of-genitive]

The English genitive alternation is known to be correlated with a number of features, including

  • Possessor.Animacy.Bin the animacy of the possessor
  • Possessor.Word.Count & Possessum.Word.Count the length in words of the possessor and possessum
  • Final.Sibilant the presence of a sibilant at the end of the possessor (Bushs prestige)
  • Semantic.Relation semantic relation between possessor and possessum (kinship, ownership, body-part, etc.)
  • TypeTokenRatio the type-token ratio of the local context
  • Genre the genre of the text (Newspaper, academic, fiction, etc.)
  • Corpus the corpus the token was taken from

Dataset object_relatives.rds

This is a dataset of English relative clauses taken from the Brown and Frown corpora of written US English, as well as the parallel LOB and FLOB corpora of written UK English (in all genres). This data was collected to investigate the influence of various factors on the choice relativizer, i.e. that vs. which vs. ZERO (see Hinrichs et al. 2015; Grafmiller et al. 2016).

  1. a doctrine that nobody either does or need hold
  2. mistakes which others manage to avoid
  3. the boundary conditions ___ we impose

The choice among relative pronouns in English is known to be correlated with a number of features, including

  • RCLn the length of the relative clause
  • antLN the length of the antecedent NP (both this and the above are related to the complexity of the RC context)
  • antPOS the part of speech of the antecedent
  • antNum the number of the antecedent
  • precRel prior use of a particular pronoun (structural persistence/priming)
  • variety variety (AmE or BrE)
  • time2 time period (1961 or 1991)

Like the genitive case, the goal of these studies was to investigate the factors that co-determine/correlate with the choice of relativizer, particularly that vs. which vs. ZERO

Dataset english.csv

For regression trees well use a dataset that comes from the languageR package (Baayen 2008) and gives mean visual lexical decision latencies and word naming latencies for 2284 monomorphemic English nouns and verbs, averaged for old and young subjects, with various predictor variables (see Baayen et al. 2006 for more details).

You can find more information about this dataset by consulting the documentation with ?languageR::english. There are a few columns we will be looking at in particular:

Classification trees

Classification trees are similar to logistic regression in that they are used to predict the probability of a set of two or more possible responses or outcomes. This is perhaps the most intuitive use of tree models.

A simple tree with rpart

Lets start by fitting a simple classification tree model and plot it. Well consider the effect of possessor animacy (as a binary variable) and final sibilant on the choice of genitive variant.

First well define the formula for quick calling. Here we are trying to predict the Type of genitive construction based on whether the possessor in animate or not (Possessor.Animacy.Bin), and whether the possessor ends in a sibilant sound (Final.Sibilant).

gen_fmla1 <- Type ~ Possessor.Animacy.Bin + Final.Sibilant

Well start with the rpart() function for creating trees, found in the rpart package. Well fit the model and plot it. See ?plot.rpart for help.

gen_rpart1 <- rpart(gen_fmla1, data = gens, method = "class")

Well plot the tree and tell it to add text to all nodes indicating the number of tokens in that node (use.n).

plot(gen_rpart1)
text(gen_rpart1, all = T, use.n = TRUE)
title("Genitives tree 1")  # add a title

The default splitting criterion in rpart is gini, but We can try to use a different information theoretic criteron (generally with binary outcomes the two methods almost always yield the same results).

gen_rpart1b <- rpart(gen_fmla1, data = gens, method = "class", parms = list(split = "information"))

# plot the tree.
plot(gen_rpart1b)
text(gen_rpart1b, all = T, use.n = TRUE)
title("Genitives tree 1: Information")

Making nice(r) plots

Unfortunately the basic plotting functions for rpart are rather ugly and unhelpful, but there are ways to make the output nicer.

One way is to adjust some of the plotting parameters. We can check those parameters in the documentation.

`?`(plot.rpart)

Well set the branches to have uniform length, with a slight slant, and well add a margin of whitespace around the plot.

plot(gen_rpart1b, uniform = T, branch = 0.8, margin = 0.1)
text(gen_rpart1b, all = T, use.n = TRUE)
title("Genitives tree 1: Information")

Still not optimal, but better.

Another way is to convert the tree to a party object with as.party() from the partykit package (more on this below). This is my preferred method.

# create a party plot and pass it along with the pipe operator
as.party(gen_rpart1) %>% plot

This output is much clearer.

We see that initially, the best split is between animate and inanimate possessors. Then, we look at the corresponding subsets and see that the presence of a final sibilant also has an effect. However, the it seems that the effect is limited to only the subset of the data in which the possessor is animate, as indicated by the presence of a split on the right, but not on the left.

Finally, the rattle package makes nice graphs as well with the fancyRpartPlot() function. (Youll need to have this package installed)

rattle::fancyRpartPlot(gen_rpart1)

I still prefer the partykit plots, but this is not bad.

A simple tree with partykit

Now well move on to a different tree fitting method using partykit. This package contains the function ctree() for Conditional Inference Tree. Ctrees are related to traditional classification and regression trees, except that the method offers certain advantages over the methods used in rpart, which tend to favor variables that have many possible splits or many missing values (Hothorn et al. 2006).

In more technical terms, ctree() derives splits using a permutation significance test procedure. Permutation tests work by taking the labels on the observed data points, rearranging those labels many times, and then for each rearrangement, we compute a relavant test statistic, e.g.the \(\chi^2\) statistic. This is a way of empirically obtaining the distribution of the test statistic for our data under the null hypothesis of no diference, no association, etc. After obtaining the test statistic for every permutation, we determines the proportion of the permutations that provide a test statistic greater than or equal to the one observed in the original data. If that proportion is smaller than some threshold (p < .05), then the result is signiicant at that level. The p-value then is the exact proportion of the permutations whose test statistic is greater than or equal to the statistic derived from our observed data. See

At each node, the ctree algorithm runs these permutation tests for all the binary splits we could make based on the predictors available, and chooses the split with the lowest p value. If no split obtains a p value below .05, the algorithm stops.

Lets try a simple ctree for the first genitives formula

gen_ctree1 <- ctree(gen_fmla1, data = gens)
plot(gen_ctree1)

We see from Node 1 that initially, the best split is between animate and inanimate possessors. Then, we look at the corresponding subsets and see that the presence of a final sibilant also has an effect. BUt already we can see the differencesin the splitting methods. Before, the rpart tree had a Final.Sibilant based split only with the animate subtree. But the ctree shows an additional split within the inanimate subtree as well.

# rpart tree
as.party(gen_rpart1) %>% plot

Predicting N > 2 response classes

A particularly nice thing about decision tree modesl is that they easily allow us to model multinomial responses.

Here well try to predict English relativizers with a simplified model, looking at only the object RCs (the book that/which/ you wrote).

For first pass, we can simply look at the change in relativzer use over time and across US and UK English.

# rpart
rel_rpart1 <- rpart(rel ~ variety + time2, rels, method = "class")
plot(rel_rpart1)

When we try to plot the tree, we get an error. This tells us that rpart was not able to create a decision tree from these predictors. Changing the splitting criteron doesnt affect this either.

# rpart
rel_rpart1b <- rpart(rel ~ variety + time2, rels, method = "class", parms = list(split = "information"))
plot(rel_rpart1b)

If we plot the distributions of the relativizers we can see that there is in fact a big drop in the use of which in US English over time.

ggplot(rels, aes(time2, fill = rel)) + geom_bar(position = "fill") + facet_wrap(~variety, 
    ncol = 2) + labs(y = "proportion of tokens")

Presumably the model should capture this, but it doesnt. If we add a couple more predictors for the length of the relative clause RCLn, and the length of the antecedent antLN we can get some results.

rel_rpart2 <- rpart(rel ~ variety + time2 + RCLn + antLN, rels)
plot(rel_rpart2, uniform = T, branch = 0.8, margin = 0.1)
text(rel_rpart2, all = T, use.n = TRUE)
title("Relativizers tree 1")

The numbers on the leaves show the respective counts for the 3 different relativizer types.

as.party(rel_rpart2) %>% plot()

Now we can really see whats going on. The splits are much clearer, and our leaves now show the proportions of relativizer types in each subset, which is realyl what we want to know more than the raw counts.

The rattle package also has nice visualization.

rattle::fancyRpartPlot(rel_rpart2)

But lets go back to the first relativzer tree attempt, and this time well use ctree() and see what happens.

# rpart
rel_ctree1 <- ctree(rel ~ variety + time2, rels)
plot(rel_ctree1, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8))

Here we can see that while the impurity reduction criteria yielded no splits, the conditional inference method did indeed detect strong associations among the predictors and the response. This is very much what we would expect just from eyeballing the distrinbutions of relativizers across time and variety.

ggplot(rels, aes(variety, fill = rel)) + geom_bar(position = "fill") + facet_wrap(~time2, 
    ncol = 2) + labs(y = "proportion of tokens")

This is a nice illustration of how the choice fo splitting method can dramatically influence the resulting trees. IN my experience, conditional inference trees will find more splits than trees using gini or information gain measures, and often those splits are intuitively reasonable. This is one reason I prefer ctree() over rpart().

rel_ctree2 <- ctree(rel ~ variety + time2 + RCLn + antLN, rels)
plot(rel_ctree2, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8))

More complex trees

That was easy. Now lets try to break stuff.

Take the formula below for genitive choice using more predictors motivated by prior research. These are mostly categorical predictors, so the model should be relatively simple (we hope).

gen_fmla2 <- Type ~ Possessor.Animacy.Bin + Final.Sibilant + Possessor.Word.Count + 
    Semantic.Relation.Bin + Possessor.Expression.Type + Genre + Corpus + Possessum.Word.Count + 
    PossessorTextFreq + PossessumTextFreq + Prior.Genitive

Now we fit a tree using this formula.

gen_rpart2 <- rpart(gen_fmla2, data = gens)
plot(gen_rpart2, uniform = T, branch = 0.8, margin = 0.1)
text(gen_rpart2, all = T, use.n = TRUE)

Yeahhhh.. Thats not very helpful. Try with partykit

as.party(gen_rpart2) %>% plot(gp = gpar(cex = 0.7))  # shrink the text size

Not very helpful. What about a ctree()?

gen_ctree2 <- ctree(gen_fmla2, data = gens)

An error? The problem is that before using ctree() we need to make sure the columns of the dataframe for our predictors are in the necessary format. ctree() doesnt work with character vectors, so well need to convert the relevant columns to factors.

factors <- c("Possessor.Animacy.Bin", "Final.Sibilant", "Semantic.Relation.Bin", 
    "Possessor.Expression.Type", "Genre", "Corpus", "Prior.Genitive")
gens[factors] <- lapply(gens[factors], as.factor)

Now try it.

gen_ctree2 <- ctree(gen_fmla2, data = gens)
plot(gen_ctree2, gp = gpar(cex = 0.7))

O.M.G. This is useless. We cant even read it, let alone try to interpret it.

Crazy trees like this are probably a sign that our tree may not be the best model for the purposes of learning something about the larger population our data is sampled from. The problem is that the tree-building algorithm will look for any and all possible splits in the data, regardless of whether those divisions are likely to be replicated if we were to take different samples of genitive constructions. This is the problem of overfitting: our tree model is too finely tuned to our specific dataset, thus it does not likely represent a good model of genitive variation in general. Well come back to what to do about this in a moment, but suffice it to say, we cant just unthinkingly plug formulas and data into a function and get meaningful results

But lets stop for a moment and look at regression trees.

Regression trees

With regression trees, the value shown on the leaf nodes is the expected value of the response, i.e.the mean, for the given partition of the data. Here well look at the effects of a number of predictors on lexical decision latencies in a word recognition task. Well first consider the age of the subject (AgeSubject = old or young),written frequency of the word, and the syntactic category (N or V) of the word.

lexdec_fmla1 <- RTlexdec ~ AgeSubject + WordCategory + WrittenFrequency
lexdec_rpart1 <- rpart(lexdec_fmla1, data = english)
plot(lexdec_rpart1, uniform = T, branch = 0.8, margin = 0.1)
text(lexdec_rpart1, all = T, use.n = TRUE)
title("Lexical decision times")

Try another visualisation.

as.party(lexdec_rpart1) %>% plot(gp = gpar(cex = 0.8))

The first thing to note is that word category (N or V) doesnt seem to have much of an effect. There are no category based splits in the tree. The second thing to note is that the leaves of the tree now show boxplots representin the distribution of response times for each subset of the data. This is different from the proportional barplots we saw with classification trees. From these plots, we can see that

  1. Younger participants are generally faster than older participants, and
  2. The frequency of the word has a clear effect in both age groupsmore frequent words are recognized faster regardless of age.

The mean values of the leaves are given in the rpart tree. If we take only those cases where the subject is old (the branch on the right) and the WrittenFrequency of the word is less 3.961 (Node 11), and then calculate the mean value of RTlexdec for that subset of the data, we get 6.758. This is the predicted response time for old subjects responding to words with a written frequency less than 3.961. This corresponds to the value shown in the rightmost node in lexdec_rpart1.

subset(english, AgeSubject == "old" & WrittenFrequency < 3.961) %>% .$RTlexdec %>% 
    mean()
[1] 6.758294

So what we can conclude from this tree is that age and written frequency seem to have the biggest effect on decision times, while word category has relatively little impact.

We can examine the relationship between these variables with scatter plots, where its fairly clear that age has a big effect.

# color by category
p_cat <- ggplot(english, aes(WrittenFrequency, RTlexdec)) + geom_point(aes(col = WordCategory), 
    alpha = 0.5) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "black") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", 
    color = "red") + ggtitle("Lexical decision time by frequency and category") + 
    theme(legend.position = "bottom")

p_age <- ggplot(english, aes(WrittenFrequency, RTlexdec)) + geom_point(aes(col = AgeSubject), 
    alpha = 0.5) + geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "black") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", 
    color = "red") + ggtitle("Lexical decision time by frequency and age") + 
    theme(legend.position = "bottom")

grid.arrange(p_cat, p_age, ncol = 2)

In general, I find regression trees most useful when we have only categorical predictors, and less so when we have lots of continuous predictors. Tree models are good sometimes for identifying inflection points in continuous predictors when the effects are non-linear, but I often find that simple scatterplots are just as effective for exploring relationships among continuous variables.

Getting model predictions

With rpart

We can obtain the predictions of an rpart object like so.

predict(gen_rpart1, type = "class") %>% head
 1  2  3  4  5  6 
of  s  s  s of of 
Levels: of s

We specify type = "class" to give us the predicted classes, but the default of the predict() function for classification trees returns a matrix of predicted probabilities of the response classes for each observation. Well generate thsi and convert it to a dataframe to which well add the observed and the predicted responses.

gen_rpart1_preds <- predict(gen_rpart1) %>% as.data.frame() %>% # add columns for the observed response and the predicted one.
mutate(obs = gens$Type %>% factor, pred = ifelse(s > 0.5, "s", "of") %>% factor)
head(gen_rpart1_preds, 10)
          of         s obs pred
1  0.8246115 0.1753885  of   of
2  0.2321536 0.7678464   s    s

One method for measuring model predictions is to look at the proportion of observations that the model predicts correctly.

which(gen_rpart1_preds$obs == gen_rpart1_preds$pred) %>% length(.)/nrow(gens)
[1] 0.7852349

This seems pretty good, but we need to consider the baseline to compare it against. Look at the overall distribution of genitives in the corpus

table(gens$Type)/nrow(gens) %>% round(3)

       of         s 
0.6139981 0.3860019

We can see that the balance of genitives is not even, so while we might think that comparing our models predictions to a random 50/50 guess would be a good idea, that would not take into account the imbalance in our dataset.

Suppose we pick an example at random from the gens dataset and try to guess which construction was used. Knowing nothing else, we could simply choose the more common alternate (the of-genitive) every time, and we would be correct 61.4% of the time. This is whats known as the baseline accuracy of the model. Ideally, our model should enable us to guess the construction used with an accuracy higher than the baseline.

The baseline probability of an s-genitive is 0.386, which means the baseline probability of the of-gen is 1 - 0.386 = 0.614. This is what we evaluate our models accuracy against.

We see how many obsrvations were correctly predicted by our model (our successes).

which(gen_rpart1_preds$obs == gen_rpart1_preds$pred) %>% length
[1] 4095

We can then use a binomial test to see if the proportion of model successes is significantly greater than our baseline.

binom.test(4095, nrow(gens), p = 0.614, alternative = "greater")

    Exact binomial test

data:  4095 and nrow(gens)
number of successes = 4095, number of trials = 5215, p-value <
2.2e-16
alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is greater than 0.614
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.7756682 1.0000000
sample estimates:
probability of success 
             0.7852349

There are other measures of predictive performance we can use as well.

One common statistic we are interested in is C. This the index of concordance between the predicted probability of an outcome and the observed response. C is the probability that the log odds of a randomly picked observation of the predicted outcome (e.g.the s-genitive) will be higher than a randomly picked observation of the other outcome (e.g.the of-genitive).

A C value of 0.5 indicates predictions at random, a C value of 1 indicates perfect prediction. Generally, you want a C value above 0.8

Well use the somers2() function in the Hmisc package. To use this, well need to convert the observed responses into binary values of 1 (= s-gen) and 0 (= of-gen). We choose these values because of is the reference level in gens$Type.

as.numeric(gen_rpart1_preds$obs) %>% head()
[1] 1 2 2 2 1 1
head(gen_rpart1_preds$obs)
[1] of s  s  s  of of
Levels: of s
Hmisc::somers2(gen_rpart1_preds$s, as.numeric(gen_rpart1_preds$obs) - 1)
           C          Dxy            n      Missing 
   0.7845832    0.5691664 5215.0000000    0.0000000

Our tree is good, but not great. We are probably missing some predictors.

With partykit

Predictions with ctrees work much the same, but in this case predict() will return the predicted outcome by default.

predict(gen_ctree1) %>% head

Measure how many observations were predicted correctly.

which(gens$Type == predict(gen_ctree1)) %>% length(.)/nrow(gens)
[1] 0.7852349

We can obtain the predicted probabilities for each class by specifying type = "prob" as an additional argument in the predict() function. Well again generate these matrix and convert it to a dataframe to which well add the observed and the predicted responses.

gen_ctree1_preds <- predict(gen_ctree1, type = "prob") %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
    mutate(obs = gens$Type %>% factor, pred = ifelse(s > 0.5, "s", "of") %>%

Regression trees

For regression trees we can measure the \(R^2\) similar to linear regression models.

lexdec_rpart1_preds <- predict(lexdec_rpart1)  # model predictions
cor(lexdec_rpart1_preds, english$RTlexdec)^2
[1] 0.6884427

A more informative output can be obtained with rsq.rpart(). These plots give us an idea of how much \(R^2\) changes as we add nodes to the tree.

rsq.rpart(lexdec_rpart1)

Regression tree:
rpart(formula = lexdec_fmla1, data = english)

Variables actually used in tree construction:
[1] AgeSubject       WrittenFrequency

Root node error: 112.46/4568 = 0.024618

n= 4568 

        CP nsplit rel error  xerror      xstd
1 0.499230      0   1.00000 1.00052 0.0204426
2 0.082433      1   0.50077 0.50159 0.0119728
3 0.080793      2   0.41834 0.40721 0.0101411
4 0.014317      3   0.33754 0.34222 0.0086192
5 0.011670      4   0.32323 0.32254 0.0081846
6 0.010000      5   0.31156 0.31738 0.0081447

The column CP in the output is the complexity parameter that the model uses to determine when to split. Its essentially the amount of change in \(R^2\) that the algorithm requires to make a split.

From the rpart documentation:

For regression models[] the scaled cp has a very direct interpretation: if any split does not increase the overall R2 of the model by at least cp (where R2 is the usual linear-models definition) then that split is decreed to be, a priori, not worth pursuing. The program does not split said branch any further, and saves considerable computational effort. The default value of .01 has been reasonably successful at pre-pruning trees so that the cross-validation step need only remove 1 or 2 layers, but it sometimes over prunes, particularly for large data sets.

One of the parameters that we can tweak to get a better fit is this cp.

Pruning and tuning

As weve seen, tree models are also prone to overfitting the data. Consider again the big trees based on a complex model of genitive choice. These trees are far too complicated to interpret in any useful way.

# rpart
plot(gen_rpart2, uniform = T, branch = 0.8, margin = 0.1)
text(gen_rpart2, all = T, use.n = TRUE)

# ctree
plot(gen_ctree2, gp = gpar(cex = 0.7))

Pruning with rpart

Adjusting for overfitting can be done post-hoc by pruning the tree, or it can be done prior to fitting the model by tuning the control settings of the function beforehand. Pruning is important for CARTs fit with rpart, and this can be done with prune(). We inspect the cp parameter first with printcp() to see how much to prune by.

printcp(gen_rpart2)

plot(gen_rpart2_pruned, uniform = T, branch = 0.8, margin = 0.1)

Pruning is generally not something that is done with ctrees (indeed, the technique was designed partly to make pruning unnecessary). What we should do instead, is decide how to control the growth of the tree beforehand in an unbiased way. There are a number of ways to do this.

Adjusting p-value

One way is to adjust the level of statistical significance the tree requires a test to meet before making a split. Splits are only created when a global null hypothesis can reasonably be rejected, as determined by a chosen p-value (by default, this is the standard = 0.05). You can adjust this under the ctree_control() options.

Lets set it to require a p-value of 0.001 or below:

gen_ctree2b <- ctree(gen_fmla2, data = gens, control = ctree_control(mincriterion = 0.999))  # now p < .001
# Note the value for 'mincriterion' is 1 minus the desired level: 1 - .001 =
# .999
plot(gen_ctree2b)

The tree is simpler now, but still pretty unmanageable.

Limiting branching depth

Another way to simplify the tree is to limit the maximum depth of the branching with the maxdepth argument. The default is maxdepth = Inf, but you can tell it to stop splitting after a certain number of levels is reached.

gen_ctree2c <- ctree(gen_fmla2, data = gens, control = ctree_control(mincriterion = 0.999, 
    maxdepth = 3))
plot(gen_ctree2c)

This is better, but we may be losing some predictive power. The tree is likely to make less accurate predictions, but it is at least interpretable.

Adjusting for node size

We can alternatively specify the minimum number of observations in a node in order to consider a split. For instance, the following tree will not make a split unless there are more than 1000 observations in a node.

gen_ctree2d <- ctree(gen_fmla2, data = gens, control = ctree_control(mincriterion = 0.999, 
    minsplit = 1000L))
plot(gen_ctree2d, gp = gpar(cex = 0.7))

Or we can specify the minimum number of observations that must be present in a terminal (or more generally, any child) node. This tree will not make a split if it results in a subset with fewer than 200 observations.

gen_ctree2e <- ctree(gen_fmla2, data = gens, control = ctree_control(mincriterion = 0.999, 
    minsplit = 1000L, minbucket = 200L))
plot(gen_ctree2e, gp = gpar(cex = 0.7))

These settings are designed to make the tree more conservative from an inferential point of view. Basically, it is more hesitant to make a claim about a given effect unless there is plenty of data that it can rely on.

Other options can be adjusted as needed/desired. See the documentation for ctree and ctree_control for how to do so.

Graphical parameters

Large trees can be unwieldy to plot, and the partykit package offers ways to adjust the graphical settings of your trees to help with presentation.

Fonts

Font size, face (bold, italic), and family (serif, Times, etc.) can be changed with the following parameters.

  • cex: Multiplier applied to fontsize
  • fontsize: The size of text (in points)
  • fontface: The specification of fontface can be an integer or a string. If an integer, then it follows the R base graphics standard: 1 = plain, 2 = bold, 3 = italic, 4 = bold italic. If a string, then valid values are: plain, bold, italic, oblique, and bold.italic.
  • fontfamily: Changes to the fontfamily may be ignored by some devices. The fontfamily may be used to specify one of the Hershey Font families (e.g., HersheySerif) and this specification will be honoured on all devices.
# (cex is a multiplier)
plot(gen_ctree1, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8, fontfamily = "Times New Roman"))

plot(rel_ctree1, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8, fontface = "italic"))

Line type & width (lex is a similar multiplier)

Line type (solid, dashed, etc.) and width can be adjusted with the lty and lwd or lex arguments respectively (lex is a multiplier similar to cex).

Line type can be specified using either text (blank, solid, dashed, dotted, dotdash, longdash, twodash) or number (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6). Note that lty = solid is identical to lty = 1.

plot(gen_ctree1, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8, lty = 2))  # dashed lines

plot(gen_ctree1, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8, lwd = 2))

Colors

plot(gen_ctree1, gp = gpar(cex = 0.8, col = "blue"))

Changing panels

The panels and edges themselves can be formatted as well (as we saw above)

`?`(panelfunctions)
plot(gen_ctree1, 
  inner_panel = node_barplot, # create tree with inner panels as parplots
  ip_args = list(id = T), # remove IDs from inner panels
  tp_args = list(fill = c("palegreen4", "palegreen1"))
)

plot(rel_ctree1, 
 gp = gpar(cex = .8),
 ip_args = list(id = F, pval = F), # remove IDs and pvals from inner panels
 tp_args = list(id = F)
)

# color bars
plot(rel_ctree1, tp_args = list(fill = heat.colors(3)))

Summary

Advantages of decision tree models:

  • Easy to understand. In simpler cases, trees are relatively simple to understand and interpret even for people without much background in statistics.
  • Data exploration. They provide intuitive visualizations that are a good way to explore patterns in your data, for instance, identifying nonlinear effects and complex interactions among predictors.
  • Non-parametric. Tree models dont make any assumptions about the distribution of the data, which means they require very little data preparation (unlike parametric methods such as regression).
  • Computationally quick and simple. They can work on very large datasets in reasonable amounts of time.

Disadvantages of decision tree models:

  • Overfitting. Tree models tend to overfit the data, and require pruning or tuning.
  • Sensitive to particularities of your data. This problem is similar in spirit to overfitting. Slight changes can result in different trees, which can give different predictions. This makes the results of the tree less likely to generalize to new data.
  • Overly complex trees. With large datasets and many predictors, we often get very large trees that are difficult to interpret.
  • Low accuracy. Trees are generally less accurate than other methods, e.g.regression.
  • Not ideal for continuous data. Tree models tend to lose too much information when trying to model continuous outcomes. In these cases, regression models are usually preferred.

For further reading see chapter 14 in Levshina (2015) and chapter 9.2 in Hastie et al. (2009).
